<section xml:id="sec-evalue-multiplicities" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Eigenvalue multiplicities</title>

<definition xml:id="def-multiplicities">
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n \times n</m> matrix, and let <m>\lambda = b</m> be an eigenvalue of <m>A</m>. 
If when fully factored, the characteristic polynomial <m>\det(A-\lambda I)</m> has the 
factor <m>(\lambda - b)^m</m>, then the <term>algebraic multiplicity</term> of 
<m>\lambda = b</m> is <m>m</m>. The <term>geometric multiplicity</term> of <m>\lambda = b</m> 
is the number of parameters appearing in <m>E_\lambda(A)</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
The algebraic multiplicity of <m>\lambda = b</m> is just the number of times the factor 
<m>\lambda - b</m> appears in the characteristic polynomial. The geometric multiplicity 
is essentially the `dimension' of the eigenspace <m>E_\lambda(A)</m>. For example, if 
<m>A</m> is <m>3 \times 3</m>, then an eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m> has geometric 
multiplicity 1 if <m>E_\lambda(A)</m> represents a line, geometric multiplicity 2 if 
<m>E_\lambda(A)</m> represents a plane, or 3 if <m>E_\lambda(A)</m> is all of <m>\R^3
</m>.
</p>

<!--
<p>
{\footnotesize{<term>Technical comment:</term> Technically speaking, the geometric multiplicity 
of an eigenvalue <m>\lambda</m>} is is the number of parameters appearing in <m>E_\lambda(A)</m> when 
<m>E_\lambda(A)</m> is \textit{written in a fully simplified way}. This can be made precise by 
requiring that the vectors that the parameters are coefficients of must be \textit{linearly independent}, 
using terminology from <xref ref="ch-furthervec"/>. However, for practical purposes the 
explanation given above should be clear enough}.
</p>-->

<example xml:id="ex-mult">
<statement>
<p>
  Find the multiplicities of the eigenvalues of <me>
A =
\begin{bmatrix}
  0 \amp  1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  0 \amp  1\\ 2 \amp  -5 \amp  4
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>

<p>
We first calculate the characteristic polynomial (by expanding across the first row)
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{vmatrix}
  -\lambda \amp  1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  -\lambda \amp  1\\ 2 \amp  -5 \amp  4-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
\amp  = (-\lambda)
\begin{vmatrix}
  -\lambda \amp  1 \\ -5 \amp  4-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
-
\begin{vmatrix}
  0 \amp  1 \\ 2 \amp  4-\lambda
\end{vmatrix}
\\
\amp  = -\lambda[-\lambda(4-\lambda) + 5] +2  \\
\amp  = -\lambda^3 + 4\lambda^2 - 5\lambda +2 \\
\amp  = -(\lambda  - 1)^2(\lambda - 2)
</mrow>
</md>,
after factoring. So the eigenvalues are <m>\lambda =1</m> and <m>\lambda = 2</m>. The 
eigenvalue <m>1</m> has algebraic multiplicity <m>2</m> because of the factor <m>(\lambda - 1)^2</m>. 
The eigenvalue <m>2</m> has algebraic multiplicity <m>1</m>, because it is not a repeated root.
</p>

<p>
To calculate the geometric multiplicities, we first need to calculate the eigenspaces. 
First we calculate for <m>\lambda = 2</m>:
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{c}
  A - 2I \amp  \vect{0}
\end{amatrix}
=
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  2 \amp  -5 \amp  2 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\xrightarrow{R_3\mapsto R_3 + R_1}   \amp
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -4 \amp  2 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\\
\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto R_3 - 2R_2} \amp
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
Let <m>z = t</m>, <m>t \in \R</m>. Then <m>y = t/2</m> and row 1 gives that <m>-2x+y = 0</m>, 
so <m>x = t/4</m>. So
<me>
E_2(A) = \left\{
\begin{bmatrix}
  \frac{t}{4} \\ \frac{t}{2}\\ t
\end{bmatrix}
\;\middle|\; t \in \R \right\} = \left\{
\begin{bmatrix}
  t \\ 2t\\ 4t
\end{bmatrix}
\;\middle|\; t \in \R \right\}
</me>.
This has 1 parameter, so the geometric multiplicity of <m>\lambda =2</m> is <m>1</m>.
</p>

<p>
For <m>\lambda = 1</m>, we solve
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{c}
  A -I \amp  \vect{0}
\end{amatrix}
=
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  2 \amp  -5 \amp  3 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\xrightarrow{R_3\mapsto R_3 + 2R_1}  \amp
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -3 \amp  3 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
\\
\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto R_3 - 3R_2} \amp
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  -1 \amp  1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
Let <m>z = t, t\in \R</m>. Then <m>y = t</m> and <m>x = t</m> also. So the eigenspace is 
<m>E_1(A) = \{[t, t, t] \;|\; t\in \R\}</m>, which has 1 parameter, so the geometric multiplicity 
of <m>\lambda = 1</m> is <m>1</m>. The answer is summarised in .
</p>

