</statement>
</example>

<p>
If <m>A</m> is <m>n\times n</m>, the sum of the algebraic multiplicities is <m>n</m> 
(because the characteristic polynomial has degree <m>n</m>). In <xref ref="ex-mult"/>, 
notice that the geometric multiplicity of the eigenvalues are less than or equal to 
their algebraic multiplicities. In fact, this is always true.
</p>


<theorem xml:id="thm-gleqa">
<statement>
<p>
The geometric multiplicity of an eigenvalue is less than or equal to its algebraic multiplicity.
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<remark xml:id="rmk-distinct">
<p>
Here's an important special case when the multiplicities are simple: suppose <m>A</m> is 
a <m>n\times n</m> matrix with <m>n</m> <term>distinct eigenvalues</term>. This means 
that all the algebraic multiplicities are 1. So by <xref ref="thm-gleqa"/>, all the 
geometric multiplicities are less than or equal to 1. But the geometric multiplicity of an 
eigenvalue is always at least 1. We conclude that:
</p>

<p>
If <m>A</m> is an <m>n\times n</m> matrix with <m>n</m> distinct eigenvalues, both 
the algebraic and geometric multiplicity of every eigenvalue are 1.
</p>
</remark>

